{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01BEhGsmaGC7SiGwEhBr6FzB","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the setup. There are two Ingress resources for `rate.example.com`:\n1. `rate-api` - handles `/api` path, no rate limiting\n2. `rate-health` - handles `/health` path, no rate limiting\n\nI need to add rate limiting annotations to the `rate-api` Ingress to limit `/api` to 1 QPS, while leaving `/health` unlimited.\n\nFor ingress-nginx, the rate limiting annotations are:\n- `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-rps` limits requests per second\n- `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-connections` limits concurrent connections\n\nTo achieve 1 QPS with a burst of 1 and return 429 status codes, I'll set `limit-rps: \"1\"` and `limit-burst-multiplier: \"1\"` on the `rate-api` Ingress. The default rate limiting status code in ingress-nginx is 503, but I can configure it to return 429 instead. I need to set the burst multiplier to 1 to enforce strict rate limiting at 1 request per second, since the test sends 10 requests at 0.5-second intervals (2 QPS total), which should trigger rate limiting after the first request using nginx's leaky bucket algorithm. limit-rps=1 and burst-multiplier=5, the bucket can hold up to 5 extra requests beyond the normal 1 request per second. I'm working through a concrete example with 10 requests arriving at 0.5-second intervals to understand exactly when requests get allowed versus rate-limited, but I need to be more careful about how the token bucket algorithm actually works here. , so I need to figure out what burst value ensures at least 4 of the 10 requests get rate-limited. With a 1 QPS limit and incoming traffic at 2 QPS, I'm accumulating 1 request per second of excess. Setting burst to 1 means only 2 requests total can pass through initially (the normal allowance plus the burst), then subsequent requests face rate limiting. At that sustained 2 QPS rate, roughly every other request should hit the limit, which should give me the 4+ rejections I'm looking for. I'm getting tangled up in the token bucket math here. Let me think through the nginx rate limiting more clearly: with a 1r/s rate and burst=5 with nodelay, the system allows up to 6 requests immediately (1 initial token plus 5 burst), then subsequent requests are rejected if they exceed the refill rate. For 10 requests arriving at 0.5s intervals (2 QPS), the first 6 would pass, then the remaining 4 would hit the rate limit.\n\nTo ensure at least 4 requests get rate-limited, I should reduce the burst to 1, which means only 2 requests can pass immediately before the rate limiting kicks in. The default rate limit status code in ingress-nginx is 503, which satisfies the task requirements, so I don't need to override it. I'll just apply the rate limiting annotations to the `rate-api` Ingress object.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1426,"cache_read_input_tokens":28867,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1426},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"51c517fa-72de-43bb-aff0-65c716527335","uuid":"f64a1aee-6790-4107-a3da-14e87b94aa2e","request_id":"req_011CcRMXeXCEG4efLmsgh6Ag"}
